    - ["mp3451024",  operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers._BaseSetProxy.__dict__,  "__delitem__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__ across all 8 mp subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 8 classes x 3 methods = 24 rows.
# __getitem__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __setitem__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __delitem__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# All 24 values are false.
# The proxy types (_BaseSetProxy, _BaseDictProxy, BaseListProxy) are the most
#   analytically interesting subjects here. At runtime, these proxy types relay
#   subscription, assignment, and deletion to a managed server process via IPC
#   proxy dispatch. However, none of __getitem__, __setitem__, or __delitem__ is
#   defined in their own Python-level __dict__ — the proxy dispatch mechanism
#   operates below the dunder level and is not expressed through these protocol
#   slots in the class __dict__.
# Contrast with wave 658 (mp3166): BaseListProxy __add__ and __mul__ were true
#   because those dunders ARE directly defined in BaseListProxy.__dict__. The
#   container access dunders (__getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__) are not
#   directly defined in the same way.
# multiprocessing is a process-based concurrency library; its types interact
#   exclusively through explicit method calls, subprocess lifecycle management,
#   and IPC — not through container or mapping access protocol overrides in any
#   class __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

